<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM PROTESTS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 12 19:47:59 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
During the Vietnam War, 57,600 Americans were killed, 1,400,000 South Vietnamese were killed, and 2,000,000 North Vietnamese were killed, all for absolutely nothing. After the war was over, the political situation was exactly the same as it was before the war. All of these people were slaughtered for nothing. It was completely pointless. Why did we do this? It was supposedly originally motivated by the Cold War, the Vietnam wasn't a strong ally of the Soviet Union anyway. Even if it were, so what? The political leanings of this one tiny Asian country would have a neglible effects on the geopolitics of the planet and the bipolar balance of power. To pretend that the U.S. cared about democracy in South Vietnam is laughable since we've supported military dictorships and monarchies all over the world. What's really tragic, is that by Johnson's administration, everyone in the United States desparately wanted to end the war, but disagreed sharply over how to do so. The &quot;doves&quot; wanted to end the war by just getting out. The &quot;hawks&quot; felt that the shame the U.S. losing a war would be to great, and wanted to somehow officially win the war before they could finally get out. As this rediculous argument dragged dragged on, Americans continued to be drafted and slaughtered in Vietnam. Finally, Nixon proposed a face-saving way to end to end the war: the &quot;vietnamization&quot; of the war, officially handing it over to the South Vietnamese, and to slowly withdraw American forces. Nixon believed that this way, he could get us out while avoiding the shame of a losing war. During Nixon's slow withdrawl of U.S. troops, large numbers of Americans were killed.  Those people would still be alive if Nixon had just pulled the U.S. troops out immediately. What's worse is  that the slow withdrawal did not even enable us to avoid the shame of losing a war. We had that shame anyway. It was rediculous to think that we could quietly slip out of Vietnam, tip toe of the war, and no one would notice that we had lost war. The Vietnam War cost so many lives on sides and achieved absolutely nothing. Despite this, Clinton had to actually apologize to having been a dove instead of a hawk.
